==Old English==

===Etymology===
Germanic ''*skrīþan'', from Indo-European ''*(s)kreit-, *(s)ker-'' ‘twist, turn, bend’.

Germanic cognates include Old Saxon ''scrîðan'' (Dutch [[schrijden]]), Old High German ''scrîtan'' (German [[schreiten]]), Old Norse ''skríða'' ‘creep, glide’ (Swedish [[skrida]]).

The Indo-European root also gave Latin [[crisare]] and Middle Irish ''crith'' (Breton [[skrija]] ‘tremble with fear’).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'ʃɹi:ðan/

===Verb===
'''scrīþan''' (strong verb class I: '''scrīþeþ''' ‘he glides’; '''scrāþ''' ‘he glided’; '''scriþon''' ‘they glided’; '''ġescriþen''', past participle)

# to [[move]], [[glide]], [[wander]]

